holidays.name: New Year's Day
holidays.description: New Year's Day is the first day of the year in the Gregorian calendar used in Australia and many other countries.

holidays.name: Epiphany
holidays.description: Many people in countries such as Australia annually observe Epiphany on January 6.

holidays.name: Orthodox Christmas Day
holidays.description: Many Orthodox Christian churches in countries such as Australia observe Christmas Day on or near January 7 in the Gregorian calendar.

holidays.name: Orthodox New Year
holidays.description: Many Orthodox Christian churches in countries such as Australia celebrate New Year’s Day on January 14 in the Gregorian calendar.

holidays.name: Tu B'Shevat (Arbor Day)
holidays.description: Tu B’Shevat is known as the “New Year for Trees”, is one of the four Jewish New Years.

holidays.name: Australia Day
holidays.description: Australia Day is the Australian national day. It is celebrated on January 26 each year.

holidays.name: Isra and Mi'raj
holidays.description: Isra and Mi'raj (Isra Me'raj, Israa and Mi'raaj, Laylat Al-Isra wa Al-Miraj, Lailat al Miraj, Night Journey and Ascension to Heaven) marks the night when the Prophet Mohammad traveled from Mecca to Jerusalem, ascended to heaven and returned.

holidays.name: Lunar New Year
holidays.description: Lunar New Year marks the first day of the New Year in the Chinese calendar.

holidays.name: Carnival / Shrove Tuesday / Pancake Day
holidays.description: Shrove Tuesday is the day before the start of the Lent period for many Christians in Australia.

holidays.name: Ash Wednesday
holidays.description: Ash Wednesday marks the first day of Lent in for many Christians in Australia.

holidays.name: Valentine's Day
holidays.description: Valentine’s Day, which is annually held on February 14, is one of the most romantic days in the year for many people in countries such as Australia.

holidays.name: Ramadan Start
holidays.description: Many Muslims in Australia welcome Ramadan as period of fasting, self-evaluation and spiritual growth. Ramadan is the ninth month in the Islamic calendar.

holidays.name: St Patrick's Day
holidays.description: St Patrick’s Day is a popular observance in Australia to honor Irish culture and commemorate one of Ireland’s patron saints, St Patrick.

holidays.name: March Equinox
holidays.description: March Equinox in Australia (Sydney)

holidays.name: Harmony Day
holidays.description: Harmony Day is a national observance that celebrates Australia’s cultural, linguistic and religious diversity on March 21 every year.

holidays.name: Palm Sunday
holidays.description: Palm Sunday in Australia celebrates Jesus Christ’s entry into Jerusalem. It is also the Sunday before Easter Sunday.

holidays.name: Purim
holidays.description: Purim commemorates a time when Jewish people were saved from death around the fourth century BCE, according to the Book of Esther.

holidays.name: Maundy Thursday
holidays.description: Many Christians in the Australia celebrate Maundy Thursday on the Thursday before Good Friday.

holidays.name: Good Friday
holidays.description: Good Friday is two days before Easter Sunday and is a national holiday in Australia.

holidays.name: Holy Saturday
holidays.description: Holy Saturday is the day before Easter Sunday and is a public holiday in some states and the two territories in Australia.
holidays.locations: ACT, NSW, NT, Qld, SA, Vic, Heard and McDonald Islands

holidays.name: Easter Sunday
holidays.description: On Easter Sunday, Christians celebrate the resurrection of Jesus Christ after his crucifixion.

holidays.name: Easter Monday
holidays.description: Easter Monday is the day after Easter Sunday and is a nationwide holiday in Australia.

holidays.name: Laylatul Qadr (Night of Power)
holidays.description: Laylat al-Qadr is most likely to be held on one of the last 10 days of month of Ramadan in the Islamic calendar.

holidays.name: Daylight Saving Time ends
holidays.description: Daylight Saving Time ends in Australia

holidays.name: Eid ul Fitr
holidays.description: Eid al-Fitr, which is on the first day of the Islamic month of Shawwal, marks the end of the month-long fast of Ramadan.

holidays.name: First day of Passover
holidays.description: Passover is a Jewish observance of the liberation from slavery and the Israelites' exodus from Egypt around 3000 years ago.

holidays.name: ANZAC Day
holidays.description: ANZAC Day is the anniversary of the landing of troops from Australia and New Zealand on the Gallipoli Peninsula in Turkey during in World War I.

holidays.name: Last day of Passover
holidays.description: The last day of Passover marks the end of the Passover period, which lasts for seven or eight days.

holidays.name: Orthodox Good Friday
holidays.description: Many Orthodox Christians in Australia remember the events leading up to Jesus Christ's crucifixion on Great Friday.

holidays.name: Orthodox Holy Saturday
holidays.description: Many Orthodox Christians in Australia remember Jesus Christ’s burial and his descent into Hades on Holy Saturday.

holidays.name: Orthodox Easter
holidays.description: Many Orthodox Christians in Australia celebrate Jesus Christ’s resurrection on Easter Sunday, also known as Pascha.

holidays.name: Yom HaShoah
holidays.description: Yom Hashoah remembers the lives and sacrifices of about six million Holocaust victims who died during World War II. This observance is annually held on the 27th day of the month of Nisan.

holidays.name: Orthodox Easter Monday
holidays.description: Many Orthodox churches in Australia observe Easter Monday on the day after the Orthodox Easter Sunday date.

holidays.name: Ascension Day
holidays.description: Ascension Day is the 40th day of Easter and commemorates Jesus Christ’s ascension into heaven, according to Christian belief.

holidays.name: Mother's Day
holidays.description: Mother’s Day is celebrated in Australia on the second Sunday of May each year.

holidays.name: Yom HaAtzmaut
holidays.description: Many Jewish communities in Australia celebrate Yom Ha’Atzmaut, which is Israel’s Independence Day, on the fifth day of the month of Iyar in the Jewish calendar.

holidays.name: Pentecost
holidays.description: Many Christians in Australia observe Pentecost, also known as Whitsunday or Whit Sunday.

holidays.name: Whit Monday
holidays.description: Whit Monday is a Christian observance also known as Pentecost Monday. It is the day after Pentecost, or Whitsunday.

holidays.name: Trinity Sunday
holidays.description: Many churches in Australia observe Trinity Sunday, a Christian feast that occurs on the first Sunday after Pentecost.

holidays.name: Lag B'Omer
holidays.description: Many Jewish Australians observe Lag B’Omer on the 18th day of the month of Iyar in the Jewish calendar.

holidays.name: National Sorry Day
holidays.description: National Sorry Day is an Australia-wide observance that acknowledges the impact of Australia’s Stolen Generations.

holidays.name: Corpus Christi
holidays.description: Corpus Christi is a Christian observance that honors the Holy Eucharist.

holidays.name: Queensland Day
holidays.description: Queenslanders commemorate their state’s birthday on Queensland Day in Australia.

holidays.name: King's Birthday
holidays.description: The King’s birthday is an annual public holiday in parts of Australia celebrating the official birthday of King Charles III.
holidays.locations: ACT, NSW, NT, SA, Tas, Vic, Heard and McDonald Islands

holidays.name: Shavuot
holidays.description: Shavuot, also known as the Festival of Weeks, is one of three major Jewish festivals celebrated among many Jewish Australians.

holidays.name: Eid al-Adha
holidays.description: Many Muslims in Australia celebrate Eid al- Adha around the 10th to the 13th days of the Islamic month of Dhu al-Hijjah.

holidays.name: June Solstice
holidays.description: June Solstice in Australia (Sydney)

holidays.name: First Day of NAIDOC Week
holidays.description: First Day of NAIDOC Week is a observance in Australia

holidays.name: Muharram/Islamic New Year
holidays.description: The first day of Muharram, which is the first month in the Islamic calendar, marks the start of the Islamic New Year.

holidays.name: Ashura
holidays.description: Ashura is a Muslim in Australia

holidays.name: Tisha B'Av
holidays.description: Tisha B’Av is on the ninth day of the month of Av in the Jewish calendar.

holidays.name: Assumption of Mary
holidays.description: The Feast of the Assumption of Mary is an annual Christian observance in Australia held on August 15. It is considered a Holy Day of Obligation - a day when some Christian denominations are obliged to attend mass.

holidays.name: Fathers' Day
holidays.description: Father’s Day celebrates the contribution that fathers and father figures make to their children’s lives.

holidays.name: Milad un Nabi (Mawlid)
holidays.description: Eid Milad ul-Nabi marks the anniversary of the Prophet Muhammad's birth and death.

holidays.name: September Equinox
holidays.description: September Equinox in Australia (Sydney)

holidays.name: Rosh Hashana
holidays.description: Rosh Hashana, also spelled Rosh Hashanah, is commonly known as the Jewish New Year. The event begins on the first day of Tishrei (or Tishri), which is the seventh month in the Jewish calendar.

holidays.name: Feast of St Francis of Assisi
holidays.description: Many churches in Australia celebrate the Feast of St Francis of Assisi to honor St Francis, the patron saint of animals and the environment, on October 4 each year.

holidays.name: Daylight Saving Time starts
holidays.description: Daylight Saving Time starts in Australia

holidays.name: Yom Kippur
holidays.description: Yom Kippur is an important Jewish holiday that falls on the 10th day of the month of Tishrei in the Jewish calendar.

holidays.name: International Pregnancy and Infant Loss Remembrance Day
holidays.description: International Pregnancy and Infant Loss Remembrance Day is a observance in Australia

holidays.name: First day of Sukkot
holidays.description: The first day of Sukkot marks the start of the Sukkot festival for Jewish communities in Australia.

holidays.name: Hoshana Rabbah
holidays.description: Many Jewish communities in Australia observe the last day of Sukkot, which marks the end of the Sukkot festival.

holidays.name: Shemini Atzeret
holidays.description: Shemini Atzeret (or Shmini Atzeret) is a Jewish holiday dedicated to the love of God, while Simchat Torah (Simchas Torah or Simhat Torah) marks the end of Sukkot and celebrates the completion of the annual reading of the Torah.

holidays.name: Simchat Torah
holidays.description: Simchat Torah (Simchas Torah or Simhat Torah) is a Jewish holiday that celebrates the completion of the annual reading of the Torah.

holidays.name: Halloween
holidays.description: Halloween is a festive occasion that is celebrated in Australian communities on October 31 each year.

holidays.name: All Saints' Day
holidays.description: Many churches in Australia annually observe All Saints' Day, also known as All Hallows' Day.

holidays.name: Diwali/Deepavali
holidays.description: Diwali, also known as the Festival of Lights, marks the beginning of the Hindu New Year.

holidays.name: All Souls' Day
holidays.description: All Souls’ Day is observed among some Christians in Australia on November 2 each year.

holidays.name: Remembrance Day
holidays.description: Remembrance Day in Australia is annually observed on November 11 although it is not a public holiday. This event remembers those who died as a result of war, particularly from World War I onwards.

holidays.name: First Sunday of Advent
holidays.description: Many Christians mark the First Sunday of Advent as the start of the Advent season leading up to Christmas.

holidays.name: Feast of the Immaculate Conception
holidays.description: Some Christians, particularly those of Catholic faith, in Australia mark the Feast of the Immaculate Conception on or around December 8.

holidays.name: December Solstice
holidays.description: December Solstice in Australia (Sydney)

holidays.name: Christmas Eve
holidays.description: Christmas Eve in Australia is annually celebrated on December 24, which is the day before Christmas Day.

holidays.name: Christmas Day
holidays.description: Christians celebrate the birth of Jesus on Christmas Day, which is in the middle of summer in Australia.

holidays.name: First Day of Hanukkah
holidays.description: The first day of Hanukkah is the start of the Hanukkah period, which lasts for 8 days, from the 25th day of the month of Kislev to the second day of Tevet in the Hebrew calendar.

holidays.name: Boxing Day
holidays.description: December 26 is the Boxing Day holiday celebrated in Australia.

holidays.name: New Year's Eve
holidays.description: Many Australians celebrate New Year’s Eve on December 31 each year, which coincides with the date before New Year’s Day in the Gregorian calendar.
